<section class="module" id="module-4" style="background: var(--color-bg)">
  <div class="module-content">
    <header class="module-header animate-in">
      <span class="module-number">04</span>
      <h1 class="module-title">Tool Use: Making the Model Take Action</h1>
      <p class="module-subtitle">Claude doesn't act on its own -- it outputs "work orders" for your program to execute. This is the only way an agent can truly change the outside world.</p>
    </header>

    <div class="module-body">

      <!-- Screen 1: Hook + chess metaphor -->
      <section class="screen animate-in">
        <h2 class="screen-heading">Claude can't query databases or send emails -- but it can "ask someone else to do it"</h2>
        <p>Up through the previous module, all workflows remained within "LLMs talking to each other." Claude can't see the time, query a database, or send an email on its own. But <strong>you can teach it to "ask someone else to do these things"</strong> -- that's the entire secret of tool use.</p>

        <div class="callout callout-accent">
          <div class="callout-icon">♟️</div>
          <div class="callout-content">
            <strong class="callout-title">This Lesson's Metaphor: Chess Master + Chess Clock</strong>
            <p>The master (Claude) can only "think about chess" -- it can't leave the table to look up openings. You give it a few "tool cards" -- look up opening books, look up endgame tables, ask the engine for an evaluation. Each card clearly states <em>what this tool can do and what parameters it needs</em>. When it wants to use one, it presses the chess clock and states the tool name and parameters. <strong>It doesn't look things up itself -- it asks you to</strong> -- you pass the result back, and it thinks about the next move. The clock gets pressed several times throughout the game -- this is the <span class="term" data-definition="Agentic Loop. LLM call → tool execution → feed result back to LLM → LLM decides next step... cycling until the LLM says 'I'm done.' This is the underlying heartbeat of all agent systems.">agentic loop</span>.</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="pattern-cards stagger-children">
          <div class="pattern-card animate-in" style="border-top: 3px solid var(--color-actor-1)">
            <div class="pattern-icon" style="background: var(--color-actor-1)">📋</div>
            <h4 class="pattern-title">Description Is Make-or-Break</h4>
            <p class="pattern-desc">Claude looks at a tool's description to decide "when to use it / how to use it." If the instructions aren't clear, the tool gets used incorrectly.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="pattern-card animate-in" style="border-top: 3px solid var(--color-actor-3)">
            <div class="pattern-icon" style="background: var(--color-actor-3)">📐</div>
            <h4 class="pattern-title">JSON Schema Is the Contract</h4>
            <p class="pattern-desc">Use JSON Schema to describe the parameter shape -- required fields, types, examples. This is the format contract between Claude and your program.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="pattern-card animate-in" style="border-top: 3px solid var(--color-actor-4)">
            <div class="pattern-icon" style="background: var(--color-actor-4)">↩️</div>
            <h4 class="pattern-title">tool_result Must Be Fed Back</h4>
            <p class="pattern-desc">After a tool executes and returns a result, you must insert it back into the conversation history as a tool_result role and call Claude again -- otherwise Claude never learns the tool's result.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="pattern-card animate-in" style="border-top: 3px solid var(--color-actor-2)">
            <div class="pattern-icon" style="background: var(--color-actor-2)">🛑</div>
            <h4 class="pattern-title">max_iterations Is Your Lifeline</h4>
            <p class="pattern-desc">The agent loop can run away -- add an upper limit. Also detect "is it repeatedly calling the same tool" -- this is often a sign of an infinite loop.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- Screen 2: Tool definition translation -->
      <section class="screen animate-in">
        <h2 class="screen-heading">Step 1: Write a "Tool Specification"</h2>
        <p>From <code>tool_use/calculator_tool.ipynb</code> -- equip Claude with a simple calculator:</p>

        <div class="translation-block animate-in">
          <div class="translation-code">
            <span class="translation-label">CODE · Python</span>
<pre><code><span class="code-line">tools = [</span>
<span class="code-line">    {</span>
<span class="code-line">        <span class="code-property">"name"</span>: <span class="code-string">"calculator"</span>,</span>
<span class="code-line">        <span class="code-property">"description"</span>: <span class="code-string">"A simple calculator that performs basic arithmetic operations."</span>,</span>
<span class="code-line">        <span class="code-property">"input_schema"</span>: {</span>
<span class="code-line">            <span class="code-property">"type"</span>: <span class="code-string">"object"</span>,</span>
<span class="code-line">            <span class="code-property">"properties"</span>: {</span>
<span class="code-line">                <span class="code-property">"expression"</span>: {</span>
<span class="code-line">                    <span class="code-property">"type"</span>: <span class="code-string">"string"</span>,</span>
<span class="code-line">                    <span class="code-property">"description"</span>: <span class="code-string">"The mathematical expression to evaluate (e.g., '2 + 3 * 4')."</span>,</span>
<span class="code-line">                }</span>
<span class="code-line">            },</span>
<span class="code-line">            <span class="code-property">"required"</span>: [<span class="code-string">"expression"</span>],</span>
<span class="code-line">        },</span>
<span class="code-line">    }</span>
<span class="code-line">]</span></code></pre>
          </div>
          <div class="translation-english">
            <span class="translation-label">Line-by-Line Explanation</span>
            <div class="translation-lines">
              <p class="tl"><strong>Line 1:</strong> tools is a <em>list</em> -- meaning you can give Claude multiple cards at once.</p>
              <p class="tl"><strong>"name": "calculator"</strong> -- the tool's "card name." Claude uses this name to invoke it.</p>
              <p class="tl"><strong>"description" (critical):</strong> This is the <strong>most important line</strong> in tool use -- Claude reads this sentence to decide "should I use this tool." If the spec is unclear, Claude will use it wrong or skip it entirely. Write it as if instructing a smart but context-free intern.</p>
              <p class="tl"><strong>"input_schema"</strong> -- uses <span class="term" data-definition="A standard for describing the 'shape' of data in JSON. For example, this field must be a string, that field is a number, and another is required. The LLM reads the JSON Schema to know 'what parameters I should fill in.' It's the contract between Claude and your program.">JSON Schema</span> to describe the parameter shape: it needs a string called expression.</p>
              <p class="tl"><strong>"required": ["expression"]</strong> -- forces Claude to fill in this parameter, no skipping allowed.</p>
              <p class="tl"><strong>One takeaway for vibe coders:</strong> a tool's description isn't written for programmers -- it's written for Claude.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- Screen 3: Agentic loop with flow animation -->
      <section class="screen animate-in">
        <h2 class="screen-heading">Step 2: Run the Agentic Loop</h2>
        <p>When Claude decides to use a tool, it <em>doesn't give a direct answer</em> -- instead it pauses and outputs a "work order," waiting for you to execute it. Then you feed the result back, and it continues. Watch this 7-step animation of the loop:</p>

        <div class="flow-animation" data-steps='[
          {"highlight":"flow-actor-1","label":"User asks: What is 17 times 23?"},
          {"highlight":"flow-actor-2","label":"Claude receives the question + tool specifications","packet":true,"from":"actor-1","to":"actor-2"},
          {"highlight":"flow-actor-3","label":"Claude doesn't answer directly -- outputs a work order: calculator(expression=\"17*23\")","packet":true,"from":"actor-2","to":"actor-3"},
          {"highlight":"flow-actor-4","label":"Your program calls the real calculator function per the work order","packet":true,"from":"actor-3","to":"actor-4"},
          {"highlight":"flow-actor-3","label":"Calculator returns \"391\" to your program","packet":true,"from":"actor-4","to":"actor-3"},
          {"highlight":"flow-actor-2","label":"Your program inserts the result as tool_result into the conversation history","packet":true,"from":"actor-3","to":"actor-2"},
          {"highlight":"flow-actor-1","label":"Claude sees the result, gives the final answer: 17 x 23 = 391","packet":true,"from":"actor-2","to":"actor-1"}
        ]'>
          <div class="flow-actors">
            <div class="flow-actor" id="flow-actor-1">
              <div class="flow-actor-icon">👤</div>
              <span>User</span>
            </div>
            <div class="flow-actor" id="flow-actor-2">
